{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20161224065317|756439935","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Bill_Shuster","to":"Bill Shuster"}],"pages":{"961068":{"pageid":961068,"ns":0,"title":"Bill Shuster","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2016-12-30T05:22:52Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{editorial|date=April 2014}}\n{{POV lead|date=April 2014}}\n{{unbalanced|date=April 2014}}\n{{weasel|date=April 2014}}\n{{peacock|date=May 2016}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Bill Shuster\n|image        = Bill Shuster, official photo portrait, 2005.JPG\n|office       = Chair of the [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|House Transportation Committee]]\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[John Mica]]\n|successor    = \n|state1       = [[Pennsylvania]]\n|district1    = {{ushr|PA|9|9th}}\n|term_start1  = May 15, 2001\n|term_end1    = \n|predecessor1 = [[Bud Shuster]]\n|successor1   = \n|birth_name   = William Franklin Shuster\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1961|1|10}}\n|birth_place  = [[McKeesport, Pennsylvania|McKeesport]], [[Pennsylvania]],<br>[[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Rebecca Shuster {{small|(Divorced)}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/04/bill-shuster-admits-personal-relationship-with-lobbyist-117054.html |title=Shuster admits relationship with airline lobbyist |work=POLITICO}}</ref>\n|education    = [[Dickinson College]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[American University]] {{small|([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])}}\n|signature    = Bill Shuster signature.svg\n}}\n'''William Franklin \"Bill\" Shuster''' (born January 10, 1961) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|PA|9}}, serving since 2001. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He is a son of former Congressman [[Bud Shuster]].\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\n{{BLP sources section | date=December 2014}}\nShuster was born in [[McKeesport, Pennsylvania]], the son of H. Patricia (n\u00e9e Rommel) and Elmer Greinert \"Bud\" Shuster. His ancestry includes German and Irish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/shuster.htm|title=shuster|publisher=}}</ref> He graduated from [[Dickinson College]], where he earned a Bachelor of Arts in Political Science and in History. Shuster also became a member of the [[Sigma Chi|Sigma Chi Fraternity]] while at Dickinson. He then earned a [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[American University]].\n\nPrior to entering politics, Shuster worked on his family farm in Bedford County and gained management experience in his roles with Goodyear Tire, Rubber Corporation, and Bandag Incorporated. He also owned and operated an automobile dealership in [http://www.usa.com/east-freedom-pa.htm East Freedom], Pennsylvania.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2001\nAfter his father, Republican U.S. Congressman [[Bud Shuster]], resigned from congress in January 2001 following a strong rebuke from the House ethics committee, Bill Shuster ran for [[Pennsylvania's 9th congressional district]]. On February 18, 2001, he won the Republican nomination with 59% of the vote, defeating State Representative [[Patrick Fleagle]] (32%) and [[Blair County, Pennsylvania|Blair County Commissioner]] [[John Eichelberger]] (9%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=442635|title=Our Campaigns - PA District 9 - R Nomination Race - Feb 18, 2001|publisher=}}</ref> On May 15, 2001, Shuster won the special election, defeating Democrat Centre County Commissioner [[Scott Conklin]] 52%\u201344%. Shuster won nine of the district's eleven counties. Conklin won Centre (58%) and [[Clearfield County, Pennsylvania|Clearfield]] (55%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=748|title=Our Campaigns - PA District 9 - Special Election Race - May 15, 2001|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = 2001 Special Election for the 9th Congressional District| work = Commonwealth of PA \u2013 Elections Information | publisher = Pennsylvania Department of State | year = 2004 | url = http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=5&OfficeID=11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pennsylvania Department of State Election Results|url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/}}</ref>\n\n;2002\nAfter redistricting, Centre County was taken out of his district. [[Somerset County, PA|Somerset]], [[Cambria County, Pennsylvania|Cambria]], [[Indiana County, Pennsylvania|Indiana]], [[Fayette County, Pennsylvania|Fayette]], and [[Cumberland County, Pennsylvania|Cumberland]] counties were added to his district. In November 2002, he won re-election to his first full term, defeating John R. Henry 71%\u201329%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=1314|title=Our Campaigns - PA District 9 Race - Nov 05, 2002|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;2004\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2004}}\nUnlike 2002, Shuster was challenged in the Republican primary. He defeated businessman Michael DelGrosso 51%\u201349%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=5097|title=Our Campaigns - PA - District 09 - R Primary Race - Apr 27, 2004|publisher=}}</ref> In November, he won re-election to his second full term, defeating Democrat Paul Politis 70%\u201330%, winning every county in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=4323|title=Our Campaigns - PA - District 09 Race - Nov 02, 2004|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;2006\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2006}}\nShuster won re-election to his third full term, defeating Democrat Tony Barr 60%\u201340%. He lost only three counties: Clearfield, Cambria, and Fayette.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207665|title=Our Campaigns - PA - District 09 Race - Nov 07, 2006|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;2008\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2008}}\nShuster won re-election to his fourth full term, defeating Democrat Tony Barr again, 64%\u201336%. This time he won all fourteen counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=324559|title=Our Campaigns - PA - District 09 Race - Nov 04, 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2010}}\nShuster won re-election to his fifth full term, defeating Democrat Tom Conners 73%\u201327%, winning all fourteen counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=493131|title=Our Campaigns - PA - District 09 Race - Nov 02, 2010|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2012}}\nAfter redistricting, the 9th moved even further to the west, gaining [[Westmoreland County, Pennsylvania|Westmoreland]], [[Greene County, Pennsylvania|Greene]], and [[Washington County, Pennsylvania|Washington]] counties. Shuster won re-election to his sixth full term, defeating Democrat Karen Ramsburg 62%\u201338%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=705247|title=Our Campaigns - PA - District 09 Race - Nov 06, 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;2014\nShuster was in a primary with Bedford County businessman Art Halvorson and Franklin County project manager Travis Schooley. The primary was held on May 20, 2014. Congressman Shuster won with 53% of the vote. Art Halvorson received 34% and Travis Schooley received 13%.\n\n===Political Positions===\nShuster has been a member of the Transportation and Infrastructure Committee since being elected in 2001 and was tapped [http://www.altoonamirror.com/page/content.detail/id/566423/Shuster-will-lead-US-House-transportation-panel.html?nav=756 chairman] of the committee for the 113th Congress.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shuster will lead US House transportation panel|url=http://www.altoonamirror.com/page/content.detail/id/566423/Shuster-will-lead-US-House-transportation-panel.html?nav=756|newspaper=Altoona Mirror|date=November 28, 2012}}</ref> There he will set the committee\u2019s legislative agenda, which  focuses on all modes transportation like aviation, maritime, roads, mass transit, and railroads.\n\nSitting on the House Armed Services Committee as well, Shuster has also been focusing his efforts this session on addressing the wasteful spending on the Medium Extended Air Defense System (MEADS) program, which has been deemed too expensive by the Army to complete.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mauriello|first=Tracie|title=Rep. Shuster calls [http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/state/rep-shuster-calls-missile-defense-project-too-costly-683123/ missile defense project too costly]|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/state/rep-shuster-calls-missile-defense-project-too-costly-683123/|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post Gazette|date=April 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nShuster held a 90.64 percent lifetime rating from the American Conservative Union in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=The American Conservative Union 2012 Congressional Score Card|url=http://conservative.org/ratingsarchive/uscongress/2012/}}</ref> He is a pro-life advocate evidenced by his consistent 0 percent rating by NARAL Pro-Choice America and Planned Parenthood and his 100 percent rating by the National Right to Life Committee.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Right to Life Committee NRLC Scorecard|url=http://nrlc.capwiz.com/bio/id/48694&lvl=C&chamber=H}}</ref>  A strong supporter of gun rights, Shuster has supported the interests of Gun Owners of America and received an A rating from the National Rifle Association in 2002, 2004, 2006, 2008, 2010, and 2012. Shuster does not rate highly with education unions. The National Education Association has given Shuster a grade of F and he was given a rating of 25 percent by the National Association of Elementary School Principals in 2007.<ref name=\"votesmart\">{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=55693|title=Bill Shuster's Ratings and Endorsements - The Voter's Self Defense System - Vote Smart|work=Project Vote Smart}}</ref>\n\nShuster has also been recognized by the US Chamber with their \u201cSpirit of Enterprise Award\u201d<ref>{{cite web|title=Spirit of Enterprise Awards 2012|url=http://www.uschamber.com/issues/legislators/spirit-enterprise-awards-2012|work=March 29, 2012|publisher=U.S. Chamber of Commerce}}</ref>  for his support for pro-growth and pro-business policies, the National Tax Limitation Committee<ref>{{cite web|title=National Tax Limitation Committee 112th Congressional Scorecard|url=http://limittaxes.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/112th-Congressional-Scorecard-20120917.pdf}}</ref>  for his votes for less spending and lower taxes, and the American Farm Bureau Federation<ref>{{cite web|title=AFBF Friend of Farm Bureau: 112th Congress|url=http://www.fb.org/index.php?action=legislative.112c}}</ref>  for supporting policies that help farmers.\n\nShuster recognizes America as a nation of immigrants, but he does not support amnesty for illegal aliens. He supports stronger border security with the national guard being deployed on the border. Along with a modernization of the visa program, Shuster desires a stricter set of penalties and incentives for business to hire legal workers.<ref name=\"housewebsitea\">{{cite web|url=http://www.house.gov/shuster/content/issues/immigration.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208024620/http://www.house.gov/shuster/content/issues/immigration.htm |archivedate=December 8, 2010 |df=mdy }}, I strongly support tougher laws against smugglers and drug traffickers. I also support the deployment of National Guard troops to our borders and believe a physical fence is necessary to truly secure our border.</ref>\n\nOn the subject of education, Shuster states that \u201cCongress should set strong and innovative standards for our schools to achieve.\u201d He supports lowering student loan interest rates as a method to increase the amount of students attending post secondary schools. He also supported the \u201cstudent and Teacher Safety Act\u201d which allows the search of any minor student suspected of holding illegal items in their possession.<ref name=\"housewebsiteb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.house.gov/shuster/content/issues/education.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208024830/http://www.house.gov/shuster/content/issues/education.htm |archivedate=December 8, 2010 |df=mdy }}, That is why I supported the \"student and Teacher Safety Act.\" This legislation would allow teachers to conduct the reasonable search of any minor student if they suspect a student may possess a weapon, dangerous material of illegal narcotics.</ref>\n\nShuster also served as a state co-chair for Governor Mitt Romney\u2019s Presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gleason|first=Daniel|title=Romney Holds Tele-Town Hall, Announces PA Leadership|url=http://www.politicspa.com/romney-holds-tele-town-hall-announces-pa-leadership/41060/|publisher=PoliticsPA|accessdate=September 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Shuster introduced H.R. 2125, the [[No IRS Implementation of Obamacare Act]]. He stated that the [[Internal Revenue Service]] violated the public trust and cannot be relied on to implement the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.therecordherald.com/article/20130528/NEWS/130529864#axzz2XBP9BO6l |title=From the Capitol: Pa. Reps. Todd Rock, Rob Kauffman and U.S. Congressman Bill Shuster |last1=Rock |first1=Todd |date=May 28, 2013 |publisher=The Record Herald |accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nShuster sponsored The Water Resources and Redevelopment Act of 2013 (WRRDA).  He sponsored this bill from his position as the House Chairman of the Transportation and Infrastructure Committee.\n\nIn January 2014, Shuster created a bipartisan panel of legislators to examine ways to use public-private partnerships to carry out various types of projects, such as water infrastructure, transportation and economic development, according to ''Ripon Advance''.<ref>(2014-01-21). \"[http://riponadvance.com/news/shuster-seeks-enhance-public-private-partnerships/6296 Shuster seeks to enhance public-private partnerships] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202063937/http://riponadvance.com/news/shuster-seeks-enhance-public-private-partnerships/6296 |date=February 2, 2014 }}\". ''Ripon Advance''. Retrieved January 21, 2014.</ref>\n\n;Legislation sponsored\n* [[Home Heating Emergency Assistance Through Transportation Act of 2014 (H.R. 4076; 113th Congress)]] \u2013 Shuster introduced this bill on February 25, 2014.<ref name=4076sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4076 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4076|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref> The bill would create an emergency exception to existing [[Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration]] (FMCSA) regulations.<ref name=\"4076sum\"/> The exceptions would allow truckers to drive for long hours if they are delivering home heating fuels, such as [[propane]], to places where there is a shortage.<ref name=PeteColdsnap>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=Cold snap prompts wave of energy bills|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/energy-environment/199575-cold-snap-prompts-wave-of-energy-bills|accessdate=March 5, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=February 28, 2014}}</ref> Shuster argued in favor of the bill saying that the bill \"will provide relief for millions of Americans suffering from the current propane and home heating fuel emergency.\"<ref name=EaseAccess>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House votes to ease access to home heating oil|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/votes/199849-house-votes-to-ease-access-to-home-heating-oil|accessdate=March 5, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=March 4, 2014}}</ref> According to the Congressman, an \"exceptionally cold winter\" increased demand on propane, \"which is used for heating approximately 12 million homes in the United States.\"<ref name=\"EaseAccess\"/>\n* [[Transparent Airfares Act of 2014 (H.R. 4156; 113th Congress)]] \u2013 Shuster introduced this bill on March 6, 2014.<ref name=4156allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4156 \u2013 All Actions|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4156/all-actions|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> The bill would change government regulations about how airlines advertise fares so that they could advertise the base fare and separately list the government imposed taxes and fees.<ref name=4156sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4156 \u2013 Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4156|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref><ref name=cbo4156>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 4156|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45289|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n;Legislation supported\nThe [[Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation Act of 2014 (H.R. 4005; 113th Congress)]] is a bill that would amend laws that govern the activities of the [[United States Coast Guard]] (USCG), the [[United States Maritime Administration|Maritime Administration]] (MARAD) within the [[United States Department of Transportation|Department of Transportation]], and the [[Federal Maritime Commission]] (FMC).<ref name=4005cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4005 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45168|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref> Shuster spoke in favor of the bill, describing it as a bill that \"ensures the men and women of the Coast Guard have the tools they need to carry out their critical missions, enforce our laws on U.S. waters and on the high seas, and safeguard our Nation's maritime interests around the world.\"<ref name=TransportPR>{{cite web|title=Committee Leaders Introduce Coast Guard & Maritime Transportation Bill|url=https://transportation.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=369179|publisher=House Transportation Committee|accessdate=April 1, 2014|author=Jim Billimoria|author2=Justin Harclerode|date=February 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities|Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]''' (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Army Corps Reform Caucus\n* Congressional Azerbaijan Caucus \u2013 Co-Chairman<ref name=\"Co-Chairman of the Congressional Azerbaijan Caucus made a statement regarding the Black January 1990 in Azerbaijan\">{{cite news|title=Co-Chairman of the Congressional Azerbaijan Caucus made a statement regarding the Black January 1990 in Azerbaijan|url=http://en.trend.az/regions/world/usa/1982748.html|accessdate=January 28, 2012|newspaper=Trend.az|date=January 22, 2012}}</ref>\n* Depot Caucus\n* Intelligent Transportation Caucus\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n* Older Americans Caucus\n* Sportsmen's Caucus\n* Congressional Cement Caucus\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat-inline}}\n* [http://www.house.gov/shuster/ Congressman Bill Shuster] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.billshusterforcongress.com/ Bill Shuster for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Pennsylvania/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Bill_Shuster_%5BR-9%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|williamshuster}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = s001154 | ballot = Bill_Shuster | nndb = 461/000040341 | votesmart  = 55693 | govtrack = 409888 | opencong = 409888 | rollcall = 13450 | politifact = | fec = H2PA09035 | opensecrets = N00013770 | assets = william-shuster | legistorm = 478/Rep_William_Shuster.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = PA/Bill_Shuster.htm | congress = bill-shuster/1681 | worldcat = | cspan = 89108 | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAcujSAP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bud Shuster]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Pennsylvania|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Pennsylvania's 9th congressional district]]|years=2001\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Mica]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[United Stat